Google Capstone / Cyclistic bike-share

ADAM ZANUB

2023-11-08

My Task :

The business task is to get clear and deep insights by finding out the answer to the main question we have :

How do annual members and casual riders use Cyclistic bikes differently?

Data Source:

  • I used Cyclistics historical trip data to analyze and identify trends.

  • I downloaded the data from the following link: URL data source

  • The data has been made available by Motivate International Inc.under this license

  • The data were collected during the year 2023, for the first quarter of the year.

# start station

# Creating  a dataframe which include missing values with two columns (latitude &longitude) 
missing_value_start <- bike_share %>%
                          select(start_station_name, start_station_id,
                                       start_lat,start_lng) %>%
                           filter(is.na(start_station_name)
                                 ) %>%
                           mutate(
                    nochar_lat=nchar(start_lat),
                    nochar_lng=nchar(start_lng)
                                 )

# Check out decimal places in latitude and longitude
checK_lat_start <- missing_value_start[missing_value_start$nochar_lat > 5
                                  |missing_value_start$nochar_lat < 2, ]

check_lng_start <- missing_value_start[missing_value_start$nochar_lng > 6
                                  |missing_value_start$nochar_lng < 5, ]

NOTE1

  • In both columns start station name & start station id there are 88104 NAs

  • for latitude the range of decimal places > [0, 2]

  • for longitude the range of decimal places > [1,2]

# end station
# creating the same previous dataframe  for end station
missing_value_end <- bike_share %>%
                        select(end_station_name, end_station_id,
                               end_lat,end_lng) %>%
                        filter(is.na(end_station_name)
                               ) %>%
                        mutate(
                        nochar_lat=nchar(end_lat),
                        nochar_lng=nchar(end_lng)
                              )   

# Check out decimal places in latitude and longitude
checK_lat_end <- missing_value_end[missing_value_end$nochar_lat > 5
                                    |missing_value_end$nochar_lat < 2, ]

check_lng_end <- missing_value_end[missing_value_end$nochar_lng>6
                                    |missing_value_end$nochar_lng < 5, ]

NOTE2

  • In both columns end station name & end station id there are 93016 NAs

  • For latitude the range of decimal places > [0, 2]

  • For longitude the range of decimal places > [1,2]

  • Through checK_lat_end & check_lng_end I have revealed a total of 426 missing values completely. Station and coordinate information are completely missing.

  • We need coordinates out to at least five (5) decimal places to be usable in terms of locating, However, in this data we only have (2) decimal places at the best. It may be caused by the companys GPS system failing which resulted in the inability to determine the station name and station ID.

The proportion of customers

# Create a data frame to help us visualize the data
total_customer <-bike_share1 %>%
                    count(member_casual)

total_customer <- total_customer %>%
                    rename(total_riders = n)

entire_no_customer <- 638997
multiply_by_ahundred <- 100

total_customer <- total_customer %>%
                        mutate(percentage_customer =
            total_riders/entire_no_customer*multiply_by_ahundred)

#rounding up to the second decimal point:
total_customer$percentage_customer <- 
                round(total_customer$percentage_customer,digits = 2)

# Cumulative sums to spot the  texts on the plot in the right position
total_customer$running_total <-
                     cumsum(total_customer$percentage_customer) - 
                                    0.5 * total_customer$percentage_customer

ylabel_position <- 100 - total_customer$running_total

# VIZ

pie_chart <- ggplot(total_customer, aes(x="", y=percentage_customer,
                                      fill=member_casual)) +
    geom_bar(stat="identity",linewidth=2, color = "white") +
    coord_polar("y", start= 0)

pie_chart+
    ggtitle("The Propotion of customers")+
    theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 20),
          axis.title = element_blank(),
          axis.text = element_blank(),
          axis.ticks = element_blank(),
          panel.grid = element_blank(),
          panel.border = element_blank())+
    scale_fill_manual(values = c("#00ff7f", "#32cd32"),
                                      name = "Customer Type")+
